re use, display, pattern, and memory could share the same surface. The use of flower and rabbit anchors the composition and gives the viewer a direct point of entry into its subject.","why_it_matters":"It matters because it treats thread, pattern, and domestic labor as serious cultural evidence."},{"id":"bastet-cat","category":"sculpture","maker":null,"hook":"A poised bronze cat with a goddess carried on its chest.","story":"This bronze cat comes from a long Egyptian tradition in which animal form and divine presence could overlap. The figure is associated with Bastet, a goddess linked with cats, protection, fertility, and household well-being. Its upright posture and alert ears give it a controlled, watchful energy, while the image of Bastet on the chest makes the body carry its meaning openly. What makes it effective is the tension between familiarity and sacredness. It is recognizable as a cat, but it also asks to be read as a protective object with ritual weight. It was made to be used, seen, kept, or exchanged, which is why its material choices still matter.","why_it_matters":"It shows how an animal image can be affectionate, sacred, and protective all at once. It also keeps the object's original purpose legible, not just its age or title."},{"id":"bayeux-tapestry-oath-scene","category":"textile","maker":"Unknown embroiderers","hook":"History stitched as a long moving sequence.","story":"The Bayeux Tapestry tells political history through thread, gesture, and procession. Its scenes feel almost cinematic before cinema existed. The scene belongs to a long embroidered narrative made to explain conquest, oath, and political legitimacy through images that could be read in sequence. It was made to be used, seen, kept, or exchanged, which is why its material choices still matter.","why_it_matters":"It shows narrative as something that can be carried by cloth across centuries. It also keeps the object's original purpose legible, not just its age or title."},{"id":"blue-faience-hippopotamus","category":"sculpture","maker":null,"hook":"A river creature, glazed in blue, carries a whole landscape on its back.","story":"This small hippopotamus was made for a tomb, but it still feels alive: bright blue, rounded, and patterned with plants from the Nile marshes. It carries ideas of danger, renewal, and companionship in one compact object. It was made to be used, seen, kept, or exchanged, which is why its material choices still matter. The faience gives that purpose a physical character: weight, surface, durability, and a reason to look closely.","why_it_matters":"It turns a feared animal into a hopeful object, showing how craft, belief, and affection can meet in a handmade form."},{"id":"book-of-kells-chi-rho","category":"manuscript","maker":"Monastic scribes and illuminators","hook":"A page where letters become architecture, garden, and jewel.","story":"The Chi Rho page turns the opening letters of Christ's name into a full visual environment. Reading slows down because the letters are no longer only signs; they become architecture, pattern, color, and devotion. A manuscript like this required prepared skins, pigments, copying, planning, and disciplined labor. That work is visible in the density of the page. The image does not simply decorate the text. It asks the viewer to linger before moving on, making attention itself part of the religious and material experience of the book. It was made to carry reading, memory, devotion, or teaching through a physical page.","why_it_matters":"It matters because it shows a book page made as devotion, where reading, looking, pigment, and disciplined labor become one experience."},{"id":"cma-amulet-seal-in-the-form-of-a-bull-150515","category":"jewelry","maker":null,"hook":"A piece of jewelry from Mesopotamia, Sumerian, Iraq, Early Bronze Age I, c. 3250 BCE, with bull bringing its subject into focus.","story":"Amulet Seal in the Form of a Bull is a piece of jewelry from Mesopotamia, Sumerian, Iraq, Early Bronze Age I, dated c. 3250 BCE, made with limestone with black stone inlaid eyes. It was made to be worn or carried as protection, devotion, or identity in a form small enough to stay close to the body. The use of bull anchors the composition and gives the viewer a direct point of entry into its subject.","why_it_matters":"It matters because it shows belief becoming portable: protection, identity, and craft condensed into a small object."},{"id":"cma-black-and-white-bird-perched-on-a-shrub-146194","category":"manuscript","maker":"Shafi' Abbasi","hook":"A manuscript page from Iran, Isfahan, Safavid period, 1651-52, with bird bringing its subject into focus.","story":"Black and White Bird Perched on a Shrub is a manuscript page by Shafi' Abbasi, from Iran, Isfahan, Safavid period, dated 1651-52, made with opaque watercolor, ink, and gold on paper. It was made to carry reading, memory, devotion, or teaching through a physical page. The use of bird anchors the composition and gives the viewer a direct point of entry into its subject.","why_it_matters":"It matters because it shows knowledge and belief as things people designed, touched, carried, and preserved."},{"id":"cma-bull-s-head-amulet-160425","category":"jewelry","maker":null,"hook":"A piece of jewelry from Egypt, Predynastic, Naqada II-III, c. 3500-2950 BCE, with bull bringing its subject into focus.","story":"Bull's-Head Amulet is a piece of jewelry from Egypt, Predynastic, Naqada II-III, dated c. 3500-2950 BCE, made with amethyst. It was made to be worn or carried as protection, devotion, or identity in a form small enough to stay close to the body. The use of bull anchors the composition and gives the viewer a direct point of entry into its subject.","why_it_matters":"It matters because it shows belief becoming portable: protection, identity, and craft condensed into a small object."},{"id":"cma-bullfights-a-moor-caught-by-a-bull-in-the-ring-105418","category":"poster","maker":"Francisco de Goya","hook":